y marginalized communities. Written by women and queer people of colour academics and activists, the book analyses pandemic lockdowns, border controls, vaccine trials, income support and access to healthcare across eight countries in North America, Asia, Australasia and Europe, to reveal the inequities within, and between countries. Putting intersectionality and economic justice at the heart of their frameworks, the authors call for collective action to end the pandemic and transform global inequities. Contributing to debates around the effects of COVID-19 – as well as racial capitalism and neoliberal globalization at large – this research is invaluable in informing future policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCOVID-19 (Disease)xGovernment policy. 0aCOVID-19 (Disease)xPolitical aspects. 0aCOVID-19 (Disease)xSocial aspects. 0aDiscrimination in medical care. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Race & Ethnic Relations.2bisacsh1 aAkhter, Farida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlalock, Emiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDu, Xuezhi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Souza, Radha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFu, Mengzhu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaritaworn, Jin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHussain, Sabiha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuarez, Crystal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulheron, Megan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNong, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerera, Suvendrini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato